mates, and the hand of people is clear in changes during the last thousand years or so. Today, Madagascar is a microcosm of global trends. What happens there in the decades ahead can, perhaps, suggest ways to help turn the tide on the environmental crisis now sweeping the world. The Sloth Lemur’s Song is a far-reaching account of Madagascar’s past and present, led by an expert guide who has immersed herself in research and conservation activities with village communities on the island for nearly fifty years. Alison Richard accompanies the reader on a journey through space and time—from Madagascar’s ancient origins as a landlocked region of Gondwana and its emergence as an island to the modern-day developments that make the survival of its array of plants and animals increasingly uncertain. Weaving together scientific evidence with Richard’s own experiences and exploring the power of stories to shape our understanding of events, this book captures the magic as well as the tensions that swirl around this island nation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aNatural historyzMadagascar. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  alemurs, giant tortoises, flightless birds, animals, island, biodiversity, madagascar, science, zoology, biology, ecology, wildlife, nature, environment, environmentalism, conservation, preservation, extinction, endangered species, climate change, habitat loss, global warming, colonization, village, community, nonfiction, environmental crisis, gondwana.1 aHaddam, Middle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRichard, Alison, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076650940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226817576423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.c